# Self-Improvement Rules

Based on [Sashido's self-improving rules](https://www.sashido.io/en/blog/cursor-self-improving-rules). Use this to analyze the codebase over time, learn from recurring patterns, and recommend or evolve new rules.

## Rule Improvement Triggers

- New code patterns not covered by existing rules
- Repeated similar implementations across files
- Common error patterns that could be prevented
- New libraries or tools used consistently
- Emerging best practices in the codebase

## Analysis Process

- Compare new code with existing rules
- Identify patterns that should be standardized
- Check for consistent error handling (e.g. fail-hard vs silent fallback)
- Align with [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) and [docs/technical/](docs/technical/)

## Rule Updates

### Add New Rules When

- A new technology/pattern is used in 3+ files
- Common bugs could be prevented by a rule
- Code reviews or playtests repeatedly mention the same feedback
- New security or performance patterns emerge

### Modify Existing Rules When

- Better examples exist in the codebase
- Additional edge cases are discovered
- Related rules or docs have been updated
- Implementation details have changed

### Example Pattern Recognition

When you see repeated patterns (e.g. resource checks, ECS queries, radial actions), consider adding or updating a rule in `.cursor/rules/` so future sessions stay consistent.

### Rule Quality Checks

- Rules should be actionable and specific
- Examples should come from actual project code when possible
- References should point at current paths and docs
- Patterns should match [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md) and [CLAUDE.md](CLAUDE.md) directives

## Continuous Improvement

- Monitor [docs/memory-bank/progress.md](docs/memory-bank/progress.md) and [activeContext.md](docs/memory-bank/activeContext.md) for recurring issues
- Update rules after major refactors (world/gen, db, rendering)
- Cross-reference related rules and design docs
- Document deprecations and migration paths when rules change

## Rule Deprecation

- Mark outdated patterns as deprecated at the top of the rule
- Remove or archive rules that no longer apply
- Update references that pointed at deprecated rules
- Follow [cursor-rules.mdc](.cursor/rules/cursor-rules.mdc) for structure
